#If the type is transcript generate a line plot of just that transcript between the start and stop points.
for _, row in data_ann.iterrows():
    start = row['start']
    stop = row['stop']
    if row['type'] == 'exon':
        rect = patches.Rectangle((start,y-0.1), stop - start, 0.2, fill =True, edgecolor = 'black', linewidth = 0.3, facecolor = '#3A4B4C', zorder=2)
        f_ax5.add_patch(rect)
    elif row['type'] == 'transcript':
        y= -0 if row["strand"] == "-" else 1
        f_ax5.plot([start,stop], [y,y], color='black', linewidth=2, linestyle='-', zorder=0)
        f_ax5.plot([start,start], [y+0.1,y-0.1], color='black', linewidth=2, linestyle='-', zorder=0)
        f_ax5.plot([stop,stop], [y+0.1,y-0.1], color='black', linewidth=2, linestyle='-', zorder=0)
        
plt.show()

Discussion¶

Each of the 3 visualization approaches have their own uses. Version 1 is the more simple approach, it is a very clean and clear approach where each group of signals has their own plot. However it is a little harder to directly compare these signals in this way. Version 2 is a bit more messy, the heat map does highlight very well the areas where genes are amplified it can be a bit harder for people to differenciate different shades of grey. Finally, version 3 is good for direct comparrison between each group of signals. The distinct coloring and the overlapping of the plots allows for a clearer picture of which signals are stronger when. However, the overlapping does bring issues, for example for P2 we can barely see some of the spikes that are present in the data because they are hidden behind the other signals.

#Prepare the variables for the plot including colors
kmers = ["AA","AC","AG","AT","CA","CC","CG","CT","GA","GC","GG","GT","TA","TC","TG","TT"]
counts = {kmer: np.zeros(len(seq_df.iloc[0,0])) for kmer in kmers}
colors = {'AA': '#8C001D',
    'AC': '#AF002A',
    'AG': '#DC1E0A',
    'AT': '#DB540B',
    'CA': '#EB8B00',
    'CC': '#FFAB54',
    'CG': '#FFCD6F',
    'CT': '#FFEB77',
    'GA': '#FBFFAD',
    'GC': '#E9F59F',
    'GG': '#D5FF94',
    'GT': '#A7E8AB',
    'TA': '#5ACC9A',
    'TC': '#50AD99',
    'TG': '#4A88A9',
    'TT': '#4563A8'}

#For loop to select every 2-mer that matches one of the 2-mers in the list kmers and incrementing the correct index in the array counts
for s in seq_df['Column1']:
    for i in range(len(s)-1):
        kmer=s[i:i+2]
        if kmer in counts:
            counts[kmer][i] += 1
